{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 10:23:41.780247", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — enterprise OSPF network\\nDate: now\\n\\nSummary\\n- Overall reachability for the host subnets (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) is healthy: pings from many hosts to 10.200.0.2 (dns_server), 10.200.0.3..6 (web servers) and 10.200.0.7 (load_balancer) succeed with 0% packet loss.\\n- OSPF routes for the host subnets and the 10.200.0.0/24 server-farm prefix are present and appear converged on core and access routers.\\n- A separate backend network 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0/1/2) is reachable among the backend nodes and the load balancer, but it is not reachable from the host subnets (pings show many “unknown” results). This matches the design intent that backend servers should not be directly accessible from user hosts, and also corresponds to the fact that 20.200.0.0/24 is not visible in the OSPF routing shown.\\n- No device or link shows sustained packet loss in the tests performed. Some single-direction latency/jitter spikes were observed on a few host pairs and server pairs but not accompanied by packet loss.\\n\\nTests performed (data sources)\\n- Full reachability matrix (ping from each host to all others) — results parsed for success/failure, latency, jitter and “unknown” (not reachable).\\n- FRR routing table dumps (show ip route) from server_access_router, router_core_1 and router_core_2.\\n\\nKey findings and evidence\\n\\n1) Host-to-server-farm connectivity: healthy\\n- Multiple host -> 10.200.0.x pings returned 0% loss. Example:\\n  - host_2_2_2_2 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): tx=4 rx=4 loss=0.0 rtt_avg=3.515 ms\\n  - host_2_2_2_2 -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7): tx=4 rx=4 loss=0.0 rtt_avg=3.193 ms\\n- FRR route evidence (server_access_router):\\n  - \"O   10.200.0.0/24 [110/10] is directly connected, br0\" — shows the server-facing /24 is locally present and being advertised via OSPF.\\n\\n2) Backend network (20.200.0.0/24) isolation from hosts: observed and localized\\n- Many host -> backend_web_X pings are reported as status \"unknown\" (no reachability). Example:\\n  - host_2_2_2_2 -> backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2): status = unknown\\n  - dhcp_server -> backend_web_1 (20.200.0.3): status = unknown\\n- Backend nodes can reach each other and the load balancer on 20.200.0.0/24:\\n  - backend_web_0 -> backend_web_1: tx=4 rx=4 loss=0.0 rtt_avg ~0.98 ms\\n  - backend_web_0/1/2 -> load_balancer on 20.200.0.x: tx=4 rx=4 loss=0.0 rtt_avg <1 ms\\n- FRR routing tables shown for core routers contain routes to 10.200.0.0/24 but do not show any OSPF advertisement of 20.200.0.0/24 into the wider OSPF domain. This indicates:\\n  - The 20.200.0.0/24 network exists locally among backend/loadbalancer nodes but is not being advertised into the enterprise OSPF domain (or intentionally withheld) — consistent with the design note that backend web servers should not be directly accessible to hosts.\\n\\n3) OSPF convergence and routing status\\n- server_access_router shows routes learned via OSPF for 10.1.1.0/24, 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, 10.2.2.0/24 via neighbor 172.16.0.14 and directly connected 10.200.0.0/24. (Output excerpt: O>* 10.1.1.0/24 ... via 172.16.0.14; O   10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected, br0)\\n- router_core_1 and router_core_2 show OSPF routes for all host subnets and 10.200.0.0/24 (learned via appropriate neighbors). OSPF adjacency and route propagation appear established (no missing 10.200.0.0/24 in their tables).\\n- There is no evidence of flapping routes or OSPF instability in the snapshots provided; route ages show a few minutes and are stable.\\n\\n4) Latency/jitter observations (non-failure anomalies)\\n- A small number of ping entries show high jitter or transient high RTTs (examples):\\n  - host_2_2_2_1 -> host_1_2_2_2: rtt_avg=26.51 ms, rtt_min=3.229 ms, rtt_max=95.796 ms, rtt_mdev=40.002 ms (single test showed wide variance)\\n  - host_1_2_2_2 -> dns_server: rtt_avg=6.413 ms, rtt_mdev=5.789 ms\\n  - web_server_3 -> load_balancer: rtt_avg=3.154 ms, rtt_mdev=3.15 ms (max spike to 8.586 ms)\\n- These are isolated/infrequent in the dataset and not correlated with packet loss. They indicate transient latency/jitter on specific paths but not a full outage.\\n\\nLocalization of anomalies / likely root causes (based on observed data)\\n- Backend isolation: The inability for hosts to reach 20.200.0.0/24 is localized to the boundary between the host-facing OSPF domain and the backend network. Evidence:\\n  - 20.200.0.0/24 is present and functional among backend nodes and load balancer, but not visible in OSPF routing tables on the network core/access routers. Root cause in scope: the backend network is not advertised (or is explicitly filtered) into OSPF — likely by design to protect backend servers.\\n- Transient high-latency/jitter events: localized to particular host-host or host-server paths (examples listed above). Root cause possibilities (not investigating further unless requested): transient CPU contention on nodes, queuing on forwarding devices, or occasional path asymmetry. No persistent packet loss, so these are performance anomalies rather than outages.\\n\\nConclusion / overall health summary\\n- Network is largely healthy: OSPF is converged, core and distribution routers have expected routes for host subnets and the 10.200.0.0/24 server farm, and hosts can reach DNS, web servers and the load balancer with no packet loss.\\n- The backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is intentionally isolated from host subnets (observed unreachable from hosts but reachable among backend/load balancer nodes). This is consistent with the design requirement that backends not be directly accessible from hosts.\\n- No device or link shows sustained packet loss or route flapping in the available snapshots. Some isolated latency/jitter spikes were observed on a few flows.\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- (a) verify whether 20.200.0.0/24 is intentionally withheld from OSPF (show FRR config on server_access_router/load_balancer), or\\n- (b) dig deeper into the paths showing high jitter (tracepath/traceroute and device interface stats),\\n- (c) collect FRR OSPF neighbor/state and LSDB dumps to confirm advertisement/filtering details.\\n\\nI will not propose mitigations unless you ask., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='e013baf9-76e8-4dc0-9ff2-8f1434b4c3a2'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
